label("$C$",(1,2.5),N);
label("$D$",(-.5,-1.25),S);
label("$X$",(0,0),NW);
[/asy] Since $\angle BXC=70^\circ,$ then $\angle AXC = 180^\circ - \angle BXC = 110^\circ.$

Since $\angle AXC = 110^\circ,$ then $\angle DXA = 180^\circ - \angle AXC = 70^\circ.$

Therefore, $x=\boxed{70}.$

(Alternatively, we could note that when two lines intersect, the vertically opposite angles are equal so $\angle DXA=\angle BXC =70^\circ.$)

Recall that $a^m\div a^n=a^{m-n}$ for positive integers $m>n$ and $a^m\cdot a^n=a^{m+n}$. Now we can write $5^5\div5^4-5^3+5^2\cdot5^1$ as $5^1-5^3+5^3$. Using the definition of subtraction and the associative property of addition, we get \begin{align*}
5^1-5^3+5^3&=5^1+-5^3+5^3\\
&=5^1+(-5^3+5^3)\\
&=5^1+0\\
&=\boxed{5}.
\end{align*}

