It's certainly possible to just calculate the complex number $2\omega^2-4\omega-30$ by just plugging in the value of $\omega$, but it's computationally simpler to use the fact that $|ab|=|a||b|$ and our knowledge of factoring quadratics: \begin{align*}
|2\omega^2-4\omega-30|&=|2(\omega-5)(\omega+3)|\\
&=2|\omega-5|\cdot|\omega+3|\\
&=2|-4-5i|\cdot|4-5i|\\
&=2\sqrt{(-4)^2+5^2}\sqrt{4^2+5^2}\\
&=\boxed{82}
\end{align*}

The greatest common factor of $28z^{97}$ and $7z^{96}$ is $7z^{96}$. We factor $7z^{96}$ out of both terms to get\begin{align*}
28z^{97}+7z^{96} &= 7z^{96}\cdot 4z +7z^{96}\cdot 1\\
&= \boxed{7z^{96}(4z+1)}.
\end{align*}

From $r = \frac{9}{5 - 4 \cos \theta},$
\[5r - 4r \cos \theta = 9.\]Then $5r = 9 + 4r \cos \theta = 4x + 9,$ so
\[25r^2 = (4x + 9)^2 = 16x^2 + 72x + 81.\]Hence, $25x^2 + 25y^2 = 16x^2 + 72x + 81.$  We can write this in the form
\[\frac{(x - 4)^2}{25} + \frac{y^2}{9} = 1.\]Thus, the graph is an ellipse with semi-major axis 5 and semi-minor axis 3, so its area is $\boxed{15 \pi}.$

